{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"48c1b2b2-a392-4d2c-bf09-23f0a63c34a5","content":"There's no documentation on this topic in the current repository. However, I can answer from general .NET knowledge:\n\n**Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump`:**\n\n1. **Enable macOS core dumps:**\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n\n2. **Set the core dump directory** (macOS stores them in `/cores/` by default):\n   ```bash\n   ls /cores/\n   ```\n\n3. **Reproduce the crash** — run your NativeAOT app; macOS will write a core file (e.g., `/cores/core.<pid>`).\n\n4. **If `/cores/` is empty**, check SIP (System Integrity Protection) isn't blocking dumps. You may need to ensure your binary is properly signed or use `codesign --force --sign - <your-app>`.\n\n5. **Analyze with `lldb`:**\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your-app\n   ```\n\n6. **For .NET-level analysis**, install the `dotnet-sos` SOS plugin:\n   ```bash\n   dotnet tool install -g dotnet-sos\n   dotnet-sos install\n   ```\n   Then inside `lldb`, use SOS commands like `clrstack`, `dumpobj`, etc.\n\n> **Note:** NativeAOT doesn't bundle `createdump`; relying on the OS-level core dump mechanism (`/cores/`) is the standard fallback on macOS.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ab06145a-b6bc-49a1-908f-df8f04ec381b","outputTokens":355,"requestId":"D80B:2FF84E:330DC2C:381B26E:69FBF0EB"},"id":"aad56315-3856-4967-98b1-7b82d1c03a31","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:55:00.667Z","parentId":"61075118-c596-4eeb-89e4-63559433b6bb"}
